  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">A severe spinal attack with neuralgia and fever has prevented William Lloyd Garrison from writing. Garrison discusses Oliver Johnson&apos;s application for an increase in salary. He has not spoken to the committee about it because the expenses for the National Anti-Slavery Standard are already so great. Some wish to discontinue the newspaper. The committee has just voted to engage Harriet Martineau as a correspondent at Â£50 per annum. He hopes that the subscription list will increase so as to allow for raising Oliver Johnson&apos;s salary. He refers to the expense of city living. Garrison&apos;s house &quot;is a semi-hotel&quot; for anti-slavery friends and visitors. He discusses Arnold Buffum&apos;s obituary, written by Lewis Tappan. The anniversary of their society is approaching and Garrison mentions some prospective speakers.</subfield>
